(Reuters) - The Department of Justice recently reached a settlement with Black Lives Matter protesters who sued after being violently cleared from Washington D.C.'s Lafayette Park in June 2020, but the agreement comes as some states continue their effort to narrow the rights of public demonstrators. This report features commentary from Scott Michelman of the ALCU of D.C., Elly Page of the International Center For Not-For-Profit Law, and Professor Tim Zick of William & Mary Law School. Our Standards: The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles. Alex Cohen produces multimedia projects on legal trends, key cases, and industry issues. He can be reached at alex.cohen@thomsonreuters.com. You can follow him on Twitter @alexlcohen.